{"id":22293,"title":"Clostridium difficile infection in Brazil: a neglected problem?","abstract":"The epidemiology of Clostridium difficile infection is virtually unknown in Brazil. In this prospective study, 8.3% of patients with nosocomial diarrhea were found to have toxigenic strains of C difficile in their feces. The relevant risk factors for Clostridium difficile infection were receipt of solid organ transplantation and septic shock. ","date":"2014-03-31","categories":"Bacterial Infections and Mycoses","split":"test","url":"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24559593","annotations":[{"name":"Clostridium difficile","weight":0.910027,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clostridium_difficile"},{"name":"Septic shock","weight":0.869327,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Septic_shock"},{"name":"Epidemiology","weight":0.822105,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidemiology"},{"name":"Diarrhea","weight":0.798641,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diarrhea"},{"name":"Feces","weight":0.790758,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feces"},{"name":"Organ transplantation","weight":0.788465,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organ_transplantation"},{"name":"Shock (circulatory)","weight":0.7654,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shock_(circulatory)"},{"name":"Infection","weight":0.72904,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infection"},{"name":"Sepsis","weight":0.704378,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sepsis"},{"name":"Strain (biology)","weight":0.704197,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strain_(biology)"},{"name":"Brazil","weight":0.70277,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brazil"},{"name":"Nosocomial infection","weight":0.615767,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nosocomial_infection"},{"name":"Clostridium","weight":0.212523,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clostridium"},{"name":"Ri